<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Intensity to Salmon Preparation Method</strong> - Grilled or cedar plank salmon's smoky char demands medium-bodied reds like Oregon Pinot Noir or Côtes du Rhône, while poached salmon pairs beautifully with crisp whites like Sancerre or Grüner Veltliner. The preparation's intensity should mirror the wine's weight—delicate preparations call for delicate wines, bold preparations for bolder bottles.</li>

  <li><strong>Temperature Precision for Optimal Salmon Pairings</strong> - Serve white wines at 48-52°F and light reds at 55-58°F when pairing with salmon. This slightly warmer service temperature for whites allows the wine's texture and subtle oak (in Chardonnay) to complement salmon's rich oils, while the cooler red service prevents tannins from overwhelming the fish's delicate proteins.</li>

  <li><strong>Consider Salmon's Natural Oils in Wine Selection</strong> - Atlantic salmon's higher fat content (12-15g per serving) pairs exceptionally with wines that have good acidity to cut through the richness—think Champagne, Albariño, or Burgundian Chardonnay. Leaner Pacific salmon varieties work beautifully with more delicate wines like Muscadet or young Riesling.</li>

  <li><strong>Sauce-First Pairing Strategy</strong> - The sauce often dominates salmon pairings more than the fish itself. Hollandaise or béarnaise demands rich whites like oaked Chardonnay or white Burgundy, while Asian glazes with soy and ginger call for off-dry Riesling or Gewürztraminer to balance the umami and spice components.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip the Decanter for Most Salmon Wines</strong> - Unlike hearty red meat pairings, salmon wine selections (primarily young whites and light reds) rarely benefit from decanting. The exception is mature Burgundy or aged Barolo served with grilled salmon—these benefit from 30 minutes of aeration to soften tannins and reveal tertiary aromatics that complement the fish's complexity.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Burgundy Glasses for Red Salmon Pairings</strong> - When serving Pinot Noir or other light reds with salmon, use Burgundy bowls rather than Bordeaux glasses. The wider bowl concentrates the wine's delicate fruit aromatics and prevents the tannins from seeming harsh against the fish's subtle flavors.</li>

  <li><strong>Seasonal Salmon Timing Affects Wine Choice</strong> - Wild Pacific salmon's peak season (May-September) coincides with when their flesh is firmest and most flavorful, making them ideal for more structured wines like Chablis Premier Cru or Oregon Pinot Noir. Off-season farmed salmon's softer texture pairs better with gentler wines like Provence rosé or New Zealand Sauvignon Blanc.</li>

  <li><strong>Age Consideration: Fresh vs. Smoked Salmon Pairings</strong> - Fresh salmon pairs best with young, vibrant wines (1-3 years old) that won't compete with its clean flavor. However, smoked salmon's concentrated, salty intensity can handle—and actually enhances—more mature wines like aged Champagne or 5-7 year old white Burgundy, where developed tertiary notes complement the smoking process.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing wine with wild salmon versus farmed salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Wild salmon's leaner texture and more intense flavor can handle bolder wines like Barolo or aged Burgundy, while farmed salmon's higher fat content pairs better with richer whites like oaked Chardonnay or Viognier. The preparation method also matters—wild salmon benefits from wines with higher acidity to cut through its natural oils, whereas farmed salmon's buttery texture complements wines with more body and lower acidity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve wine at different temperatures when pairing with hot versus cold salmon dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, temperature coordination enhances the pairing experience significantly. For hot salmon dishes like grilled or pan-seared, serve whites slightly warmer (50-55°F) and reds at cellar temperature (60-65°F) to match the dish's warmth. Cold salmon preparations like sashimi or smoked salmon pair best with well-chilled wines (45-50°F for whites, 55-60°F for light reds) to maintain the dish's refreshing quality.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing wine with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is choosing wines that are too heavy or tannic, which overwhelm salmon's delicate flavor profile. Many people default to big Cabernet Sauvignon or heavily oaked Chardonnay, but these wines mask the fish's subtle taste. Instead, focus on medium-bodied wines with balanced acidity like Pinot Noir, Grüner Veltliner, or unoaked Chardonnay that complement rather than compete with the salmon.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is salmon wine pairing good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Salmon is excellent for wine beginners because it's forgiving and pairs well with many different wine styles, from crisp whites to light reds. The fish's mild flavor won't clash with most wines, making it easier to experiment and learn your preferences. Start with classic pairings like Pinot Noir or Sauvignon Blanc, then gradually explore more adventurous options like Rosé Champagne or white Rhône blends.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How does the cooking method change which wine I should choose for salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Cooking method dramatically impacts wine selection because it changes the salmon's texture and flavor intensity. Grilled or blackened salmon develops smoky, caramelized notes that pair beautifully with medium-bodied reds like Côtes du Rhône, while poached salmon's delicate preparation calls for lighter whites like Albariño or Muscadet. Cedar plank smoking adds woody aromatics that complement oaked wines, whereas raw preparations like sashimi need bright, mineral-driven wines like Chablis or Sancerre.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What affordable wine alternatives work well with salmon under $20?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Excellent budget-friendly options include Washington State Pinot Noir ($15-18), which offers the perfect weight and acidity for salmon, and Portuguese Vinho Verde ($8-12) for lighter preparations. Spanish Verdejo ($12-16) provides crisp minerality that enhances grilled salmon, while Oregon Pinot Gris ($14-18) offers the body and texture to complement richer salmon dishes. These wines deliver restaurant-quality pairings without the premium price tag.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair the same wine with salmon sushi and cooked salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While possible, it's not ideal because the preparations have vastly different flavor profiles and textures. Salmon sushi's clean, raw taste pairs best with high-acid, mineral wines like Champagne or Sancerre that cleanse the palate, while cooked salmon can handle wines with more body and complexity. If you must choose one wine, opt for a versatile Pinot Noir from Burgundy or Oregon that can adapt to both preparations reasonably well.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do salmon marinades and sauces affect wine pairing choices?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Marinades and sauces often become the dominant flavor, requiring you to pair with the sauce rather than the salmon itself. Teriyaki glaze calls for off-dry Riesling or Gewürztraminer to complement the sweetness, while lemon-herb marinades pair beautifully with crisp Sauvignon Blanc or Vermentino. Creamy dill sauces need wines with enough richness like white Burgundy, and spicy Asian marinades work well with aromatic whites like Viognier or rosé wines that can handle the heat.</p>
  </div>
